'''Nahe Shrine''' (なへじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Hamatome, {{ill|lt=Yaizu|Q696783|qid=Q696783|1=Yaizu}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|qid=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}.

=== Overview ===
[[File:Nahe-jinja-torii.jpg|thumb|<center>Torii of Nahe Shrine</center>]]
Because it stands at the foot of Tōme-yama ({{ill|lt=Kokūzō-yama (Shizuoka Prefecture)|Q64712681|qid=Q64712681|lt=Kokūzō-yama|1=Mount Kokuzo}}), a {{ill|lt=shintai-zan|Q1595289|qid=Q1595289|lt=kannabi mountain|1=Sacred mountains}}, it is also called "Kokūzō-san."

Shrine tradition says it was founded in Year 3 of {{ill|lt=Emperor Keitai|Q349277|qid=Q349277|1=Emperor Keitai}} ({{ill|lt=509|Q30977|qid=Q30977|1=509}}) through a solicitation by the {{ill|lt=Mononobe clan|Q1755836|qid=Q1755836|1=Mononobe clan}}.

It is also said that it was first worshiped at a sacred rock in the sea off Nabesaki, and later moved to Tōme-yama (Kokūzō-yama).

It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} listed in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'. In the '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Suruga no Kuni Jinmyōchō|1=UNKNOWN}}', it appears as "Nahe Tenjin" with Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q215646|qid=Q215646|1=Edo}}, it was also called Nabeshima Daimyōjin, Nabe Shrine, and Nabesaki Daimyōjin.

During the {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} period's {{ill|lt=separation of Shinto and Buddhism|Q1970535|qid=Q1970535|1=Shinbutsu bunri}}, it was separated from Ganjō-ji.

